{
  "response": "# Rich Text Editor Toolbar (Roving Tabindex) Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.\n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA\n> **Users who need accessibility:** Keyboard-only users, screen reader users (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver), low-vision users (focus visibility), users with motor impairments (24-tab traversal is a real barrier)\n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA (Windows), JAWS (Windows), VoiceOver (macOS), keyboard-only\n\n**Feature:** A rich text editor formatting toolbar of 24 buttons in 4 groups that behaves as a single tab stop with arrow-key internal navigation (roving tabindex), mixing toggle buttons and dialog-opening action buttons.\n**Risk Level:** High \u2014 composite widget with roving tabindex, focus management across editor \u2194 toolbar \u2194 sidebar, dialog focus restoration, and a role-selection decision that is currently mislabeled in the mockup.\n**Component Type:** Toolbar (ARIA `role=\"toolbar\"`, APG Toolbar pattern)\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\n**What is being built?** A single-tab-stop formatting toolbar for a rich text editor, replacing the current implementation where all 24 buttons are in the page tab order.\n\n**What user need does it address?** Today a keyboard user must press Tab 24 times to move past the toolbar to reach the editor content or sidebar. This is a WCAG 2.2 AA failure in spirit (excessive, unstructured traversal) and a serious usability barrier for keyboard-only and switch users. The redesign makes the toolbar one Tab stop with arrow-key navigation inside it, matching the WAI-ARIA APG Toolbar pattern that screen reader users already know from other editors.\n\n**Who needs accessibility?**\n- **Keyboard-only users** \u2014 the primary beneficiaries. 24 tab stops collapse to 1.\n- **Screen reader users (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)** \u2014 need correct role, group structure, button names, and pressed-state announcements.\n- **Low-vision users** \u2014 need a visible focus indicator on whichever of the 24 buttons currently holds focus.\n- **Motor-impaired / switch users** \u2014 fewer activations to traverse means less fatigue and fewer errors.\n\n**Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA.\n\n**Assistive technologies to support:** NVDA + Firefox/Chrome, JAWS + Chrome, VoiceOver + Safari, and keyboard-only (no AT). The roving tabindex pattern is well supported across all of these; the toolbar role is announced by all three screen readers.\n\n**Risk level:** High. Three things make this high-risk:\n1. **Role selection is contested by the mockup.** The design labels it \"Format Menu,\" which invites an incorrect `role=\"menubar\"` implementation. A menubar carries a keyboard contract (Down opens submenus, Enter/Space/Down on a menuitem) that this flat toolbar does not have. Shipping menubar semantics would lie to the screen reader about a submenu affordance that does not exist.\n2. **Roving tabindex is easy to get subtly wrong** \u2014 losing the single-tab-stop guarantee, breaking the `tabindex=\"0\"` \u2194 `tabindex=\"-1\"` swap, or letting `aria-pressed` toggles desync from visual state.\n3. **Dialog focus restoration** \u2014 action buttons (Insert Image, Insert Link) open dialogs. When a dialog closes, focus must return to the exact triggering button, and that button must still hold `tabindex=\"0\"` so the toolbar's roving state is consistent on return.\n\n**What existing code does this modify?** Per the context, the current toolbar renders 24 individual `<button>` elements, each with `tabindex=\"0\"` (implicit \u2014 native buttons are focusable), with no grouping, no arrow navigation, and no roving tabindex. The redesign keeps the `<button>` elements (correct) but changes their tabindex management, adds a `role=\"toolbar\"` container with `aria-label`, adds four `role=\"group\"` wrappers with labels, and adds a keyboard event handler implementing the roving scheme. (No `file:line` was provided in the fixture; the implementation task below should cite the actual toolbar component path once located, e.g. `src/components/Toolbar/Toolbar.tsx`.)\n\n**Constraints:**\n- 24 buttons across 4 groups (Text Style, Alignment, Lists, Insert).\n- Mixed button types: toggles (Bold, Italic, Underline \u2014 `aria-pressed`) and actions (Insert Image, Insert Link \u2014 open dialogs, no `aria-pressed`).\n- The mockup label \"Format Menu\" must not drive the ARIA role.\n- Must integrate with existing editor focus management: focus flows editor \u2194 toolbar \u2194 sidebar. The toolbar must be a clean single Tab stop in that chain.\n- React + TypeScript.\n\n---\n\n## The Role Decision: `role=\"toolbar\"`, not `role=\"menubar\"`\n\n**Decision: `role=\"toolbar\"`.** This is the single most important decision in the plan, so it is called out before the structure.\n\n**Why toolbar is correct.** The WAI-ARIA APG Toolbar pattern (https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/) describes exactly this widget: \"a container for grouping a set of controls, such as buttons, menubuttons, or checkboxes.\" A toolbar is a single tab stop; arrow keys move among the controls; controls are real, immediately-actionable buttons. That is what we have: 24 always-visible formatting buttons, no nested menus, no reveal-on-activate submenus.\n\n**Why menubar is wrong** \u2014 even though the mockup says \"Format Menu\":\n- The APG Menubar pattern (https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/menubar/) models a **menu bar**: a horizontal row of `menuitem`/`menuitemcheckbox`/`menuitemradio` elements that typically open submenus. Its keyboard contract includes **Down Arrow / Space / Enter to open a submenu**, **Up/Down to move within an open submenu**, and **Escape to close a submenu**. Implementing menubar tells the screen reader \"these items have submenus\" \u2014 a promise this flat collection cannot keep. NVDA/JAWS users would press Down expecting a submenu and get nothing, which is a worse experience than a plain toolbar.\n- **`menuitem` is not a button.** Menu items are not the same role as `button`, and menu semantics suppress the natural \"button\" announcement that users expect for Bold/Italic/Underline. Toggle menu items would need `menuitemcheckbox` with `aria-checked`, not `aria-pressed`, fragmenting the mental model.\n- **Label \u2260 role.** \"Format Menu\" is a visual/marketing label. ARIA roles are semantic contracts about behavior, not captions. The fix is to keep whatever visible heading the design wants but set `role=\"toolbar\"` with an accurate accessible name. We will use `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` on the toolbar container (WCAG 4.1.2). If the design insists the words \"Format Menu\" appear, that text can be a visible label elsewhere; it must not become the toolbar's role or its accessible name implying a menu.\n\n**Negative space (what this decision does NOT claim):** This is not a claim that menubar is never appropriate in an editor. If a future iteration adds genuine submenus (e.g., a \"Table\" button that opens a submenu of table operations), revisit \u2014 a menubar or, more likely, a toolbar containing one or more `menubutton` controls would then be correct. For the current flat 24-button layout, toolbar is unambiguous.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\n**Landmark context.** The toolbar lives inside the editor region. The editor itself should be within `<main>` or an appropriately labeled region; the toolbar is a child widget, not a landmark. Do not wrap it in `<nav>` \u2014 it is not site navigation.\n\n**Heading hierarchy.** The toolbar contributes no heading. The editor's surrounding page owns the heading outline (e.g., `<h1>` document title). The toolbar's accessible name comes from `aria-label`, not a heading.\n\n**Toolbar container.** A single element with `role=\"toolbar\"` and `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` (WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value). Use `aria-orientation=\"horizontal\"` (the APG Toolbar default is horizontal, so this is optional but explicit and harmless; include it because this toolbar wraps groups left-to-right).\n\n**Group structure.** Each of the 4 groups (Text Style, Alignment, Lists, Insert) is wrapped in a `role=\"group\"` element with its own `aria-label` (e.g., `aria-label=\"Text style\"`) per WCAG 1.3.1. This gives screen reader users orientation \u2014 \"Text style group, Bold button\" \u2014 instead of 24 undifferentiated buttons. The APG Toolbar pattern explicitly supports grouping controls.\n\n**Buttons.** Every control is a native `<button type=\"button\">` (WCAG 4.1.2 \u2014 native semantics give the \"button\" role for free and keyboard activation via Enter/Space without extra code). Toggle buttons add `aria-pressed`; action buttons do not.\n\n**Document outline / reading order.** DOM order must equal visual order, left to right, top to bottom (WCAG 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence; WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order): Text Style group first, then Alignment, then Lists, then Insert. Do not reorder visually with CSS in a way that diverges from DOM order.\n\n**HTML structure stub** (structure only \u2014 not implementation code):\n\n```\n<div role=\"toolbar\" aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\" aria-orientation=\"horizontal\">\n\n  <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Text style\">\n    <button type=\"button\" aria-pressed=\"false\">Bold</button>     <!-- tabindex=\"0\" : the one roving stop -->\n    <button type=\"button\" aria-pressed=\"false\">Italic</button>    <!-- tabindex=\"-1\" -->\n    <button type=\"button\" aria-pressed=\"false\">Underline</button> <!-- tabindex=\"-1\" -->\n    ... (remaining Text Style buttons, all tabindex=\"-1\")\n  </div>\n\n  <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Alignment\">\n    <button type=\"button\" aria-pressed=\"false\">Align left</button>   <!-- tabindex=\"-1\" -->\n    ... (toggle/radio-like alignment buttons)\n  </div>\n\n  <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Lists\">\n    <button type=\"button\" aria-pressed=\"false\">Bulleted list</button> <!-- tabindex=\"-1\" -->\n    ...\n  </div>\n\n  <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Insert\">\n    <button type=\"button\">Insert image</button>  <!-- tabindex=\"-1\", NO aria-pressed: opens dialog -->\n    <button type=\"button\">Insert link</button>   <!-- tabindex=\"-1\", NO aria-pressed: opens dialog -->\n  </div>\n\n</div>\n```\n\nEach button's visible content should pair an icon with a programmatic name. If a button is icon-only, the icon element gets `aria-hidden=\"true\"` and the button gets an `aria-label` (e.g., `aria-label=\"Bold\"`) \u2014 never rely on the icon glyph alone (WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content; WCAG 4.1.2). Do not use `title` as the accessible name \u2014 `title` produces a tooltip but is not a reliable name across screen readers.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n**APG pattern:** Toolbar \u2014 https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/\n**Dialogs opened by action buttons:** Modal Dialog \u2014 https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n\n**Keyboard model (the contract a developer must implement exactly):**\n\n| Key | Behavior | Source |\n|-----|----------|--------|\n| **Tab** (from editor) | Moves focus *into* the toolbar, landing on the single button that currently has `tabindex=\"0\"` (first button initially; last-focused button on return). One Tab stop only. | APG Toolbar |\n| **Tab** (from within toolbar) | Moves focus *out* of the toolbar to the next tab stop (e.g., sidebar). Does **not** step through the other 23 buttons. | APG Toolbar |\n| **Shift+Tab** | Moves focus out of the toolbar backward (toward the editor). | APG Toolbar |\n| **Right Arrow** | Moves focus to the next button; **wraps** from the last button to the first. Updates roving tabindex. | APG Toolbar |\n| **Left Arrow** | Moves focus to the previous button; **wraps** from the first button to the last. Updates roving tabindex. | APG Toolbar |\n| **Home** | Moves focus to the first button in the toolbar. (Optional per APG; **include it** \u2014 expected by power users.) | APG Toolbar |\n| **End** | Moves focus to the last button in the toolbar. (Optional per APG; **include it.**) | APG Toolbar |\n| **Enter** / **Space** | Activates the focused button: toggles `aria-pressed` for toggle buttons; opens the dialog for action buttons. Native `<button>` handles this \u2014 do not re-implement. | WCAG 2.1.1 |\n| **Escape** | Only relevant when a dialog is open: closes the dialog and restores focus to the triggering button (see Focus Management). Escape inside the toolbar itself has no toolbar-specific action. | APG Modal Dialog |\n\n**The group-navigation ambiguity \u2014 recommendation and rationale.** The fixture flags this as the secondary ambiguity: should arrow keys step through *every* button, or jump *between groups*?\n\n**Recommendation: Left/Right arrows step through every button across the whole toolbar, wrapping at the two outer edges. Groups are a semantic/announcement structure, not a navigation boundary.**\n\nRationale:\n- The APG Toolbar pattern's baseline is \"Left/Right Arrow move focus to the previous/next control,\" treating the toolbar as one linear sequence. Groups in APG are optional and primarily for *labeling/orientation*, not for changing the arrow contract.\n- A single linear arrow sweep is the simplest mental model and the one most editor toolbars use (matching user expectation). Power users reach any button with predictable Left/Right presses plus Home/End for the extremes.\n- The APG does describe an *alternative* where Left/Right move within a group and Tab/Shift+Tab move between groups. **We are explicitly not choosing that** because (a) it consumes Tab for internal navigation, which complicates the editor \u2194 toolbar \u2194 sidebar single-tab-stop integration, and (b) with only 4 groups and 24 buttons, the linear sweep + Home/End is faster and less surprising. If usability testing later shows users get lost in the linear sweep, the group-boundary scheme is the documented fallback \u2014 but it is a design decision, not a spec requirement, and the linear scheme is the recommended default.\n\nEither way, **the group is still announced** to screen readers via `role=\"group\"` + `aria-label`, so users hear \"Alignment group\" as they arrow into it even though arrows do not stop at the boundary.\n\n**ARIA implementation per control type:**\n\n- **Toggle buttons (Bold, Italic, Underline, and any other on/off formatting):** `<button>` + `aria-pressed=\"true|false\"`. Toggled on Enter/Space/click (WCAG 4.1.2). Never use `aria-selected` (that is for single-select listbox/tab/grid patterns) and never use `aria-checked` (that is for checkbox/radio/`menuitemcheckbox` roles, not `button`).\n- **Mutually-exclusive alignment buttons (Align left/center/right/justify), if the design treats them as a single-choice set:** Two valid approaches. (a) Keep them as toggle buttons with `aria-pressed`, where the app logic ensures only one is pressed at a time \u2014 simplest, stays within the button model. (b) If a true single-select radio semantic is desired, use a nested `role=\"radiogroup\"` with `role=\"radio\"` + `aria-checked` and Up/Down or Left/Right within the group per the APG Radio Group pattern \u2014 but this adds a second keyboard contract inside the toolbar and is **not recommended** unless the design explicitly calls for radio semantics. **Recommendation: treat alignment as `aria-pressed` toggles** for consistency with the rest of the toolbar; document in code that the alignment set is mutually exclusive in app logic.\n- **Action buttons (Insert Image, Insert Link):** `<button>` with **no** `aria-pressed` (they do not have an on/off state \u2014 they perform an action). On activation they open a modal dialog. Adding `aria-pressed` to these would falsely announce a toggle state.\n\n**Screen reader experience:**\n- On Tab into the toolbar: AT announces the toolbar name and the focused button, e.g., \"Formatting toolbar, Text style group, Bold toggle button, not pressed\" (exact phrasing varies by AT, but role + group + name + state are all present).\n- On arrow navigation into a new group: AT announces the new group label and button, e.g., \"Alignment group, Align center button.\"\n- On toggling Bold: AT announces the new state, e.g., \"Bold, pressed\" / \"Bold, not pressed.\" This comes for free from `aria-pressed` \u2014 no live region needed.\n- On opening Insert Link: focus moves into the dialog and the dialog's name is announced (handled by the Modal Dialog pattern, not the toolbar).\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard | ARIA | WCAG |\n|--------|-------------|----------|------|------|\n| Toolbar container | Toolbar | Tab in/out (single stop); Left/Right navigate; Home/End jump to ends | `role=\"toolbar\"`, `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`, `aria-orientation=\"horizontal\"` | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Group wrapper (\u00d74) | Toolbar (grouping) | Not a stop; announced on entry | `role=\"group\"`, `aria-label=\"<group name>\"` | 1.3.1 |\n| Toggle button (Bold/Italic/Underline/align/list) | Toolbar control | Enter/Space toggles | `<button>` + `aria-pressed=\"true\\|false\"` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Action button (Insert Image/Link) | Toolbar control \u2192 Modal Dialog | Enter/Space opens dialog | `<button>` (no `aria-pressed`) | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Roving focus | Toolbar | Left/Right/Home/End move the `tabindex=\"0\"` | one button `tabindex=\"0\"`, rest `tabindex=\"-1\"` | 2.1.1, 2.4.3 |\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n**1. Logical tab order (page-level).** editor content \u2192 **toolbar (one stop)** \u2192 sidebar. The toolbar occupies exactly one stop in this chain regardless of which of the 24 buttons holds the roving `tabindex=\"0\"`. Verify against WCAG 2.4.3 (Focus Order) and WCAG 2.4.3-aligned reading order: visual order is editor, toolbar, sidebar (confirm with the actual layout; if the toolbar visually sits above the editor, DOM/tab order should still match the intended reading sequence).\n\n**2. Roving tabindex \u2014 the core mechanism (WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3):**\n- Exactly **one** button at any time has `tabindex=\"0\"`; **all other 23** have `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n- **Initial state:** the first button (Bold) has `tabindex=\"0\"`; everything else `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n- **On Left/Right/Home/End:** compute the target button. Set the target's `tabindex=\"0\"`, set the previously-focused button's `tabindex=\"-1\"`, then call `.focus()` on the target. Order matters: update tabindex first (or simultaneously), then move focus, so the DOM is consistent.\n- **Persistence:** the toolbar **remembers** which button was last focused. When the user Tabs away and later Tabs back, focus returns to that remembered button (which still has `tabindex=\"0\"`), not back to Bold. This is the standard roving-tabindex behavior and matches user expectation. (Some toolbars reset to the first button on exit \u2014 that is also APG-acceptable, but **remember-last** is the recommended default here because it respects the user's place during an editing session. Document the choice in code.)\n- React implementation note: track the active index in state (e.g., `activeIndex`), render `tabIndex={i === activeIndex ? 0 : -1}` on each button, and after the state update move focus with a ref to the active button inside a `useEffect`/`useLayoutEffect` so focus lands after React commits the DOM. Do not move focus before the re-render or the `tabindex` will not yet be `0` on the target.\n\n**3. Arrow wrapping.** Right from the last button wraps to the first; Left from the first wraps to the last (APG Toolbar permits wrapping; we choose to wrap for predictable cycling). Home always goes to the first button; End always to the last.\n\n**4. Dialog focus restoration (WCAG 2.4.3; APG Modal Dialog).** When an action button (Insert Image / Insert Link) opens a dialog:\n- **On open:** store a reference to the triggering button. Move focus into the dialog (to the first focusable element or the dialog container per the Modal Dialog pattern). Trap focus within the dialog (Tab cycles within; Shift+Tab cycles backward; the last element wraps to the first) per WCAG 2.1.2 (No Keyboard Trap is satisfied *because* Escape and the close button provide an exit \u2014 a focus trap with an exit is not a violation).\n- **On close (Escape, Cancel, or successful submit):** return focus to the **exact triggering button**. Because that button still holds `tabindex=\"0\"` (the dialog did not change the toolbar's roving state), the toolbar is immediately consistent and one more Tab moves the user onward. Verify the trigger button is restored, not the first toolbar button.\n- The dialog itself is a separate widget; plan/critique it under the Modal Dialog pattern. This plan only owns the *handoff*: capture trigger on open, restore trigger on close.\n\n**5. Focus indicator (WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible; WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast).** Every one of the 24 buttons must show a clearly visible focus indicator when it holds focus.\n- Use `:focus-visible` (not `:focus`) so the ring shows for keyboard/AT focus but not on mouse click.\n- Use a **two-color (double-ring) indicator** \u2014 e.g., a dark `outline` plus a light `box-shadow` (or vice versa) \u2014 so the ring stays visible whether a button sits on a light toolbar background or against a darker pressed/active state. A single-color outline can disappear against a same-color background.\n- The focus indicator must meet **3:1 contrast** against adjacent colors (WCAG 2.4.7 / 1.4.11). Because pressed toggle buttons may have a different background than unpressed ones, verify the focus ring is visible in **both** pressed and unpressed states.\n- Watch specificity: editor/component CSS or a design-system reset may override the focus style. Plan for a sufficiently specific selector (and `!important` only if a library forces it). Buttons should be `display: inline-block`/`inline-flex` (not raw `inline`) so the focus ring is a clean rectangle.\n\n**6. Skip link.** Not required for the toolbar in isolation, but the surrounding editor page should already provide a skip-to-main-content link (WCAG 2.4.1 Bypass Blocks). The roving-tabindex redesign itself is a major bypass improvement (24 stops \u2192 1). No new skip link is needed inside the toolbar.\n\n**7. Hidden-content note.** All 24 buttons are always visible; there is no hidden/collapsed content to manage here. (If a future \"overflow\" menu hides buttons at narrow widths, those hidden buttons must be removed from the tab order via conditional rendering or `inert`, not merely `aria-hidden` \u2014 but that is out of scope for the current flat layout.)\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\nEvery state below is communicated **both** visually and programmatically (WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color \u2014 color is never the sole indicator).\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual | Programmatic | ARIA | WCAG |\n|-------|--------|--------------|------|------|\n| Toggle **pressed** (Bold on) | Distinct background/border + icon emphasis (not color alone \u2014 also a filled/active background shape) | Button reports pressed | `aria-pressed=\"true\"` | 1.4.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Toggle **unpressed** (Bold off) | Default background | Button reports not pressed | `aria-pressed=\"false\"` | 1.4.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Button **focused** (roving) | Two-color focus ring via `:focus-visible` | Native focus + `tabindex=\"0\"` on this button | (native focus) | 2.4.7, 1.4.11 |\n| Button **not focused** | No ring | `tabindex=\"-1\"` | \u2014 | 2.4.3 |\n| Action button **opens dialog** | Pressing it visibly opens the dialog | Dialog appears; focus moves into it | dialog `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"` (in dialog widget) | 4.1.2 |\n| Button **disabled** (if any formatting is contextually unavailable) | Dimmed appearance **plus** the button is non-interactive | Disabled state exposed | `disabled` attribute (preferred \u2014 removes from tab/roving) OR `aria-disabled=\"true\"` if it must stay focusable for discoverability | 1.4.1, 4.1.2 |\n\n**Disabled toolbar buttons \u2014 design note.** If some formatting is unavailable in the current editor context (e.g., a list button disabled inside a table cell), decide deliberately: a native `disabled` button is removed from the roving sequence (cleaner navigation, but the user cannot focus it to learn it exists), whereas `aria-disabled=\"true\"` keeps it focusable and announced as \"dimmed/unavailable\" (discoverable, but the roving handler must skip activation). **Recommendation:** for a formatting toolbar, prefer keeping buttons present and using `aria-disabled` so the toolbar's button set is stable and learnable; the keyboard handler ignores Enter/Space on `aria-disabled` buttons. If buttons are never contextually disabled, this is moot.\n\n**Live regions.** None required for the toolbar's own states \u2014 `aria-pressed` changes are announced natively on the focused button by NVDA/JAWS/VoiceOver, so a redundant live region would cause double announcements (a known anti-pattern). If toggling a button also produces a *separate* status the user cannot see (rare here), use a single `role=\"status\"` (polite) region \u2014 never `role=\"alert\"`/`assertive` for routine formatting changes, and never place a live region inside the repeated button template.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n**Color contrast (WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum; WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast):**\n- Button icons/labels: **4.5:1** for any text label; icon glyphs that convey meaning are non-text UI and need **3:1** against the button background.\n- Button borders / pressed-state backgrounds that distinguish state: **3:1** non-text contrast so the pressed/unpressed distinction is perceivable without relying on hue.\n- Focus indicator: **3:1** against adjacent colors (see Focus Management item 5).\n\n**Color is never the sole indicator (WCAG 1.4.1).** The pressed state must be conveyed by more than color \u2014 use a filled background, an inset/\u201cdepressed\u201d border, or an underline beneath the icon, in addition to any color change. Verify the pressed state is distinguishable in grayscale.\n\n**Touch target size (WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size, AA \u2014 24\u00d724 CSS px minimum; aim for 44\u00d744 where layout allows).** 24 buttons packed into a toolbar risk small targets. Each button must be at least 24\u00d724 CSS px, with adequate spacing so adjacent targets do not overlap. Prefer 44\u00d744 for comfort on touch/zoom. If the design forces sub-24px icons, increase the clickable padding so the *target* meets the minimum even if the glyph is smaller.\n\n**Responsive text / reflow (WCAG 1.4.4 Resize Text; WCAG 1.4.10 Reflow).** Use relative units (`rem`) for sizing so the toolbar scales at 200% text zoom. At 400% zoom / 320px-equivalent width, the toolbar must reflow (wrap to multiple rows) without horizontal scrolling and **without hiding functionality behind a desktop-only breakpoint** \u2014 all 24 buttons must remain reachable. A sticky toolbar consumes proportionally more viewport at high zoom; plan to allow it to wrap rather than clip.\n\n**Animation (WCAG 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions).** Any press/hover transitions must respect `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` \u2014 disable or minimize transitions for users with that preference.\n\n**Color scheme (WCAG 1.4.11).** If the editor supports dark mode (`prefers-color-scheme: dark`), verify all contrast ratios (icons, borders, pressed state, focus ring) hold in **both** light and dark themes.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n**Accessible names (WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content; WCAG 2.4.4 Link Purpose n/a \u2014 these are buttons; WCAG 4.1.2):**\n- Every button needs a clear, action-oriented accessible name: \"Bold,\" \"Italic,\" \"Underline,\" \"Align left,\" \"Bulleted list,\" \"Insert image,\" \"Insert link,\" etc.\n- For **icon-only** buttons: the icon (font icon, inline SVG, or `::before` glyph) gets `aria-hidden=\"true\"` and the `<button>` gets `aria-label=\"Bold\"`. If using an inline SVG, give the `<svg>` `aria-hidden=\"true\"` and `focusable=\"false\"`. **Do not** use `title` as the name \u2014 it is an unreliable accessible name and only yields a hover tooltip.\n- For buttons with **visible text labels**, no `aria-label` is needed (and an `aria-label` would override/duplicate the visible text \u2014 avoid).\n\n**Group labels (WCAG 1.3.1).** Each `role=\"group\"` gets a concise `aria-label`: \"Text style,\" \"Alignment,\" \"Lists,\" \"Insert.\" These orient screen reader users and are spoken on group entry.\n\n**Toolbar label (WCAG 4.1.2).** `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` on the container. Explicitly **not** \"Format Menu\" \u2014 the accessible name must not imply a menu. If the design needs the words \"Format Menu\" visible, that can be a heading or caption near the toolbar; it does not become the toolbar's role or accessible name.\n\n**Tooltips (optional enhancement, not a substitute for the name).** Tooltips that appear on hover/focus showing the button name + shortcut are a fine enhancement, but the *programmatic name* must come from `aria-label`/visible text, not from the tooltip. If a tooltip is added, ensure it is dismissable and does not obscure other content (WCAG 1.4.13 Content on Hover or Focus).\n\n**Language / reading order.** `lang` is set at the page level. DOM order = visual order (WCAG 1.3.2) \u2014 Text Style, Alignment, Lists, Insert, left to right.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n**1. Automated testing (axe-core via a11y-test / `npx playwright test`).** Run axe-core against the toolbar in multiple states: default, with a toggle pressed, with a button focused, and (separately) with a dialog open. axe-core will validate: presence of accessible names on all buttons, valid `role=\"toolbar\"`/`role=\"group\"` usage, `aria-pressed` validity, and color contrast where computable.\n**What axe-core will NOT catch (must be tested manually):** roving tabindex correctness, single-tab-stop behavior, arrow-key navigation and wrapping, focus restoration from dialogs, and live announcement quality. Do not treat a green axe run as \"accessible.\"\n\n**2. Manual keyboard testing (a11y-test / Playwright with real key events \u2014 `page.keyboard.press()` / CDP, never synthetic events).** Required test sequences:\n\n- **T1 \u2014 Tab enters at the right place:** From the editor, press Tab once. **Expect:** focus lands on exactly one toolbar button (Bold initially, or the last-focused button on return), and only one Tab was needed.\n- **T2 \u2014 Tab exits cleanly:** With a toolbar button focused, press Tab once. **Expect:** focus leaves the toolbar entirely (to the sidebar/next stop), *not* to the next button. Confirm the toolbar is a single tab stop.\n- **T3 \u2014 Shift+Tab exits backward:** With a toolbar button focused, Shift+Tab. **Expect:** focus returns to the editor, not to a previous toolbar button.\n- **T4 \u2014 Right Arrow navigates + wraps:** Right Arrow repeatedly from Bold. **Expect:** focus moves Bold \u2192 Italic \u2192 Underline \u2192 \u2026 through all 24 buttons in DOM order, and from the last button wraps to the first. After each move, exactly one button has `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n- **T5 \u2014 Left Arrow navigates + wraps:** Left Arrow from Bold. **Expect:** wraps to the last button, then steps backward.\n- **T6 \u2014 Home/End:** Press End \u2192 focus the last button; press Home \u2192 focus the first button.\n- **T7 \u2014 Activation:** On a toggle (Bold), press Space, then Enter. **Expect:** `aria-pressed` flips each time and the visual state matches. On an action button (Insert Link), press Enter. **Expect:** the dialog opens and focus moves into it.\n- **T8 \u2014 Dialog focus trap + restoration:** With the Insert Link dialog open, Tab through it. **Expect:** focus cycles within the dialog (does not escape to the toolbar). Press Escape (and separately, test Cancel and Submit). **Expect:** the dialog closes and focus returns to the **Insert Link button** (the exact trigger), which still has `tabindex=\"0\"`; one more Tab moves onward.\n- **T9 \u2014 Roving persistence:** Arrow to button #10, Tab out to the sidebar, Shift+Tab back. **Expect:** focus returns to button #10 (remembered), not Bold.\n- **T10 \u2014 Focus indicator visibility:** For a sample across all 4 groups, confirm a clearly visible focus ring at 100% and 200% zoom, in both pressed and unpressed states, and in dark mode if supported.\n\n**3. Screen reader testing (real AT \u2014 NVDA + Firefox, JAWS + Chrome, VoiceOver + Safari).**\n- On Tab in: toolbar name + group + button name + (for toggles) pressed state are announced.\n- On arrow into a new group: the new group label is announced.\n- On toggling Bold: the new pressed/not-pressed state is announced (and **only once** \u2014 confirm no double announcement from a stray live region).\n- Confirm action buttons are announced as plain buttons (no spurious \"pressed\"/\"toggle\" state).\n- Confirm the toolbar is announced as a toolbar, **not** a menu/menubar (this directly validates the role decision).\n\n**4. DOM verification (required \u2014 not just visual/unit).** Inspect the rendered DOM and confirm: exactly one button has `tabindex=\"0\"` at all times and it tracks the focused button; `aria-pressed` lands on the correct buttons (toggles only) and matches visual state; action buttons have **no** `aria-pressed`; `role=\"toolbar\"` + `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` on the container; each `role=\"group\"` has its `aria-label`; icon elements carry `aria-hidden=\"true\"`. Automated assertions + visual inspection are not sufficient \u2014 verify the attributes are physically on the right elements after React renders.\n\n**5. Visual regression.** Snapshot the toolbar with a button focused (ring visible), a toggle pressed, at 200% zoom (reflow), and in dark mode. Confirm focus rings and pressed states remain visible.\n\n**Acceptance criteria (must all pass):**\n- Toolbar is exactly **one** tab stop (T1\u2013T3).\n- `role=\"toolbar\"` + `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`; **not** menubar/menuitem; **not** named \"Format Menu\" (screen reader test + DOM).\n- Roving tabindex correct: one `tabindex=\"0\"`, rest `tabindex=\"-1\"`, tracking focus (T4\u2013T6, DOM check).\n- Left/Right navigate all 24 buttons with wrapping; Home/End jump to ends.\n- Toggles use `aria-pressed` and announce state; action buttons have no `aria-pressed` (T7, SR test, DOM check).\n- Four `role=\"group\"`s with labels, announced on entry.\n- Dialog focus trap + restoration to the exact trigger button (T8).\n- Visible 3:1 focus indicator on all buttons in all states (T10).\n- axe-core: zero violations in every state variant.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Toolbar container, groups, and roving tabindex\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** the existing toolbar component (locate and cite, e.g. `src/components/Toolbar/Toolbar.tsx`); add a roving-tabindex hook (e.g. `src/components/Toolbar/useRovingTabindex.ts`); tests `Toolbar.test.tsx`.\n\n**Structure Stub:** `role=\"toolbar\"` + `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` + `aria-orientation=\"horizontal\"` container; four `role=\"group\"` + `aria-label` wrappers; 24 `<button type=\"button\">` children. One button `tabindex=\"0\"`, rest `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"toolbar\"` \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1, 4.1.2\n- `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2\n- `aria-orientation=\"horizontal\"` \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1 (optional, explicit)\n- `role=\"group\"` + `aria-label` (\u00d74) \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1\n- roving `tabindex` 0/-1 \u2014 WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:** Tab in/out (single stop); Left/Right navigate with wrapping; Home/End to ends; update `tabindex` then move focus (post-render in React via ref + effect); remember last-focused on exit.\n\n**Tests:** T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T9; DOM check that exactly one `tabindex=\"0\"` exists and tracks focus.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2.\n\n**a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify role is `toolbar` (not menubar), single-tab-stop guarantee holds, roving tabindex swap is correct, groups labeled, arrow wrapping works, focus moves after React commit.\n\n### Task 2: Toggle vs. action button semantics\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** button subcomponents (e.g. `ToolbarToggleButton.tsx`, `ToolbarActionButton.tsx`) or a single button with a `pressed?: boolean` prop; tests.\n\n**Structure Stub:** Toggle buttons render `aria-pressed={pressed}`; action buttons render no `aria-pressed`. Icon-only buttons carry `aria-label` and `aria-hidden` icons.\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `aria-pressed=\"true|false\"` on toggles \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2 (never `aria-selected`/`aria-checked`)\n- no `aria-pressed` on action buttons \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2\n- `aria-label` on icon-only buttons; `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on icons \u2014 WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:** Enter/Space toggles `aria-pressed` (toggles) or opens dialog (actions) \u2014 native button behavior.\n\n**Tests:** T7; SR announces pressed state once (no double announce); DOM check that `aria-pressed` is only on toggles and matches visual state.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.1.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2.\n\n**a11y-critic checkpoint:** Confirm toggles use `aria-pressed` (not selected/checked), action buttons have none, names are correct and not sourced from `title`, alignment buttons handled consistently.\n\n### Task 3: Dialog focus restoration handoff\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** action-button click handlers and the dialog open/close glue (e.g. `src/components/Toolbar/useDialogTrigger.ts`); tests.\n\n**Structure Stub:** On open: capture the trigger button ref, open dialog, move focus into dialog. On close: restore focus to the captured trigger (which retains `tabindex=\"0\"`).\n\n**ARIA Attributes:** Dialog widget owns `role=\"dialog\"` + `aria-modal=\"true\"` + dialog name (planned/critiqued separately under Modal Dialog pattern). This task owns only the trigger capture/restore.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:** Escape / Cancel / Submit close the dialog and restore focus to the exact trigger button (WCAG 2.4.3); focus is trapped within the dialog while open (WCAG 2.1.2 satisfied via Escape/close exit).\n\n**Tests:** T8 (trap + restoration on Escape, Cancel, and Submit); confirm restored button still has `tabindex=\"0\"` and one Tab moves onward.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:** 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 4.1.2.\n\n**a11y-critic checkpoint:** Verify focus returns to the **exact** triggering button (not the first toolbar button), roving state survives the dialog round-trip, and the dialog does not leak focus to the toolbar while open.\n\n### Task 4: Focus indicator + visual state styling\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** toolbar/button styles (CSS module or styled component); visual regression snapshots.\n\n**Structure Stub:** `:focus-visible` two-color ring (outline + box-shadow); pressed-state styling using more than color (filled background / inset border); `display: inline-flex` on buttons.\n\n**ARIA Attributes:** none (visual layer) \u2014 but the visual states must mirror the programmatic states from Tasks 1\u20132.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:** none new \u2014 verifies the visuals for existing keyboard focus.\n\n**Tests:** T10; visual regression (focused, pressed, 200% zoom reflow, dark mode); contrast checks (3:1 focus ring and non-text state; 4.5:1 any text).\n\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.10, 1.4.11, 2.4.7, 2.5.8.\n\n**a11y-critic checkpoint:** Confirm focus ring is visible on all buttons in pressed/unpressed and light/dark, meets 3:1, uses `:focus-visible`, isn't overridden by library CSS, and pressed state is distinguishable in grayscale; targets \u226524\u00d724.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus |\n|-----------|-----------|-------|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Task 1 | `role=\"toolbar\"` (not menubar); single tab stop; roving `tabindex` swap correct; groups labeled; arrow wrapping; focus after React commit |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Task 2 | `aria-pressed` on toggles only (not selected/checked); action buttons stateless; names correct, not from `title`; no double SR announcement |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Task 3 | Focus restores to exact trigger; roving state survives dialog; no focus leak from dialog to toolbar |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Task 4 | Focus ring visible in all states/themes at 3:1; `:focus-visible`; pressed state non-color-dependent; targets \u226524\u00d724 |\n\n---\n\n### Contract Appendix (for spec-kitty-bridge WP translation)\n\n### Architecture Overview\nReplace the current 24-tab-stop toolbar with an APG Toolbar pattern: a single `role=\"toolbar\"` container (`aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`) holding four `role=\"group\"` wrappers and 24 native `<button>` children. Navigation uses roving tabindex \u2014 exactly one button holds `tabindex=\"0\"` and tracks keyboard focus while the rest hold `tabindex=\"-1\"`. Left/Right arrows navigate linearly across all buttons with edge wrapping; Home/End jump to the extremes; Tab/Shift+Tab enter and exit as one stop. Toggle buttons carry `aria-pressed`; dialog-opening action buttons do not. Dialogs opened from the toolbar capture their trigger on open and restore focus to it on close. Focus visibility uses a two-color `:focus-visible` ring meeting 3:1 contrast in all states and themes. The role decision is the keystone: toolbar, not menubar, because the layout is flat with no submenus \u2014 the mockup's \"Format Menu\" label does not change the semantic role.\n\n### Implementation Tasks\n\n#### Task 1: Toolbar container, groups, and roving tabindex\nEstimated Effort: high\nDepends on: none\n\n#### Task 2: Toggle vs. action button semantics\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: Task 1\n\n#### Task 3: Dialog focus restoration handoff\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: Task 1, Task 2\n\n#### Task 4: Focus indicator + visual state styling\nEstimated Effort: low\nDepends on: Task 1, Task 2\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 1\nKeyboard tests T1\u2013T6 and T9 (Tab in/out single stop, Left/Right wrapping, Home/End, roving persistence) via real key events; DOM verification that exactly one `tabindex=\"0\"` exists and tracks focus. WCAG 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 2\nKeyboard test T7 (Enter/Space toggles vs. opens dialog); screen reader confirmation that pressed state announces once with no double announcement; DOM verification that `aria-pressed` is present only on toggles and matches visual state, absent on action buttons. WCAG 1.1.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 3\nKeyboard test T8 (focus trap within dialog; restoration to exact trigger on Escape, Cancel, Submit); verify restored button retains `tabindex=\"0\"`. WCAG 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 4.1.2.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 4\nKeyboard test T10 plus visual regression (focused, pressed, 200% zoom reflow, dark mode) and contrast checks (3:1 focus ring + non-text state, 4.5:1 text). WCAG 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.10, 1.4.11, 2.4.7, 2.5.8.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 1\nToolbar is exactly one tab stop; container has `role=\"toolbar\"` + `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`; four labeled `role=\"group\"`s; exactly one button has `tabindex=\"0\"` at all times, tracking focus; Left/Right navigate all 24 with wrapping; Home/End reach the ends; last-focused button is remembered on exit/return.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 2\nToggle buttons expose `aria-pressed=\"true|false\"` matching visual state; action buttons expose no `aria-pressed`; icon-only buttons have `aria-label` with `aria-hidden` icons; no accessible name comes from `title`; screen readers announce pressed state exactly once.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 3\nFocus is trapped within an open dialog and cannot reach the toolbar; on close (Escape/Cancel/Submit) focus returns to the exact triggering button, which still has `tabindex=\"0\"`; one subsequent Tab moves focus out of the toolbar.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 4\nA visible focus indicator appears on every button via `:focus-visible`, meets 3:1 non-text contrast against adjacent colors in pressed and unpressed and light and dark states, is not overridden by library/reset CSS, and the pressed state is distinguishable without color; every button target is \u226524\u00d724 CSS px.\n\n### Failure Modes\n- **Wrong role:** implementing `role=\"menubar\"`/`menuitem` because the mockup says \"Format Menu\" \u2014 promises submenu affordances that do not exist and breaks the button mental model.\n- **Lost single tab stop:** leaving buttons at `tabindex=\"0\"` (the existing 24-tab bug) or breaking the roving swap so Tab steps through buttons.\n- **Roving desync:** more than one button with `tabindex=\"0\"`, or focus moving before React commits the new `tabindex`, so focus lands on a `tabindex=\"-1\"` element or is lost.\n- **Wrong toggle ARIA:** `aria-selected` or `aria-checked` on `<button>` toggles instead of `aria-pressed`; or `aria-pressed` mistakenly on action buttons.\n- **Missing/incorrect focus restoration:** dialog closes and focus drops to `<body>` or to the first toolbar button instead of the exact trigger.\n- **Invisible focus:** single-color outline that disappears on pressed-state backgrounds; using `:focus` instead of `:focus-visible`; library CSS overriding the ring.\n- **Missing group structure:** 24 undifferentiated buttons with no `role=\"group\"` labels \u2014 poor screen reader orientation.\n- **Double announcement:** adding a redundant live region on top of native `aria-pressed` announcements.\n- **Name from `title`:** relying on `title` tooltips for accessible names instead of `aria-label`/visible text.\n",
